Mast cell activation syndrome (MCAS) is characterized by excessive release of mast cell mediators in various tissues causing a range of symptoms. Flushing is a common feature of MCAS, occurring in up to 98% of patients. The likely explanation for laryngeal and/or angioedema in patients with MCAS is that the reaction is IgE- mediated, causing immediate edema. MCAS can also contribute to syncope.

Anaphylaxis is an IgE-mediated hypersensitivity reaction that typically involves a wide variety of symptoms. Symptoms can be severe or even life-threatening and occur rapidly after exposure to an allergen. However, unlike other conditions on our list. It can also happen within 30 minutes of a trigger.

Hereditary angioedema (HAE) is characterized by recurrent, episodic attacks of localized, severe swelling of the skin, often affecting the face, mouth, or extremities. Angioedema may involve the larynx and cause severe respiratory symptoms, as well.
Carcinoid syndrome refers to a complex of signs and symptoms caused by hormones secreted by a carcinoid tumor and can present as flushing of the face, neck or trunk

Acute allergic reaction to a medication is a hypersensitivity reaction that occurs within minutes to hours of taking a medication, and may include flushing. It is not typically associated with syncope, angioedema and laryngeal edema, though in severe allergic reactions these symptoms are possible in the presence of anaphylaxis.

Acute allergic reaction to food is a type I IgE-mediated hypersensitivity reaction to a food protein, and the reaction typically begins within an hour after ingestion, and may induce flushing. It is similarly not usually associated with syncope, laryngeal edema or angioedema, but these can occur rarely.

Acute intermittent porphyria (AIP) may be related to estrogen, and women are six to 10 times more likely to have symptoms than are men. AIP may also include some or all of the features of other conditions, such as flushing. Abdominal pain, particularly severe, could be the presenting feature of an attack. Peripheral and autonomic neuropathy may lead to syncope and facial swelling.

Acute stress response is frequently accompanied by physical symptoms like flushing that have no pathological cause. In high stress states, syncope and abdominal cramping can also occur, but neither is particularly frequent. Angioedema and laryngeal edema do not generally appear in an acute stress response, unless caused by a separate allergic response.

Alcohol abuse can contribute to a number of symptoms which may appear similar to those caused by other underlying medical problems. For example, alcohol may cause the release of histamine into the blood stream as it is a vasodilator and therefore histamine liberator. Histamine is associated with allergic symptoms, including facial flushing. In addition, chronic heavy drinkers may show signs and symptoms of peripheral and/or autonomic neuropathy, thereby increasing the risk of syncope. Moreover, alcohol use is associated with a heightened risk for acute pancreatitis and can trigger an attack. Acute pancreatitis can present with severe abdominal pain and vomiting. Alcohol-related malnutrition could be a contributing factor in this case, as nutritional deficiencies are associated with AIP attacks, as well. Finally, alcohol intoxication can also result in significant swelling of various areas of the face. This symptom typically resolves when the effects of intoxication wear off.

Generalized anxiety is a psychological problem, and its symptoms are rarely caused by organic problems such as medical disease, medication side effects or substance misuse. Anxiety can manifest as many physical sensations, and anxiety is a significant symptom in many underlying diseases, like carcinoid syndrome and MCAS. Flushing, laryngeal edema, syncope and angioedema are not typical symptoms in individuals experiencing generalized anxiety. However, these symptoms may appear from a separate stress-related cause, or in a panic attack, which would then fall within the range of the anxiety diagnosis.
